## Implementation Steps

- [ ] **Story 1.1: Initialize Next.js Project with Core Tooling**
  - [ ] Verify existing bootstrapped Next.js project with App Router
  - [ ] Setup folder structure based on project context
  - [ ] Set up TypeScript configuration
  - [ ] Configure ESLint and Prettier
  - [ ] Set up Husky and commitlint
  - [ ] Create Dockerfile and .dockerignore
  - [ ] Update README.md with project information
  - [ ] Create `.env.local` template with required environment variables:
    - `NEXTAUTH_SECRET` for JWT tokens
    - `NEXTAUTH_SESSION_MAX_AGE_SECONDS` (default: 1 week)
    - `NEXTAUTH_REMEMBER_ME_MAX_AGE_SECONDS` (extended session duration)
    - `DATABASE_URL` for SQLite database path
  - [ ] Create `/data` directory in project root with appropriate gitignore rules
  - Success criteria: Project successfully runs, lints, formats, and can be containerized
  - Dependencies: None

- [ ] **Story 1.2: Integrate Prisma ORM and Define Initial User Schema**
  - [ ] Install Prisma CLI and Client
  - [ ] Initialize Prisma with SQLite configuration
  - [ ] Define User model with required fields and relations
  - [ ] Define UserSetting model with fields:
    - `userId` (String, `@id`, relations to User)
    - `theme` (enum: LIGHT, DARK, SYSTEM; `@default(SYSTEM)`)
    - `menuPosition` (enum: TOP, SIDE; `@default(SIDE)`)
  - [ ] Ensure referential integrity with `onDelete: Cascade` for UserSetting when User is deleted
  - [ ] Create migration and apply to database
  - [ ] Implement seeding for default admin user
  - [ ] Implement logic to create default UserSetting record when User is created
  - Success criteria: User schema defined, migrations created, and default admin user seeded
  - Dependencies: Story 1.1

- [ ] **Story 1.3: Implement NextAuth.js for Core Authentication Logic**
  - [ ] Install NextAuth.js and Prisma adapter
  - [ ] Configure NextAuth.js API route
  - [ ] Implement Credentials provider with name/password
  - [ ] Configure JWT strategy and callbacks
  - [ ] Implement session management with HTTP-only cookies
  - [ ] Integrate secure password hashing
  - [ ] Implement "Remember Me" functionality:
    - Add checkbox to login form
    - Extend session duration based on checkbox state
    - Configure cookie maxAge dynamically
  - [ ] Include user preferences in session:
    - Fetch UserSetting record with User during authentication
    - Include theme and menuPosition in JWT payload
    - Expose these in session.user object for client-side access
  - [ ] Update User.lastLoginAt on successful authentication
  - [ ] Add comprehensive error handling for authentication edge cases
  - Success criteria: Users can authenticate with name/password, sessions properly managed
  - Dependencies: Story 1.2

- [ ] **Story 1.3.5: Create API Endpoint to List User Tiles**
  - [ ] Create API route for fetching user profiles
  - [ ] Implement transformation of User records to UserTile objects
  - [ ] Ensure proper error handling
  - [ ] Format lastLoginAt as ISO 8601 string in response
  - [ ] Implement ordering by User.createdAt (ascending)
  - Success criteria: API returns formatted user tiles with required information
  - Dependencies: Story 1.2

- [ ] **Story 1.4: Develop Rich Interactive Tile-Based Login Page UI**
  - [ ] Create login page with tile grid
  - [ ] Implement user tile visuals with avatar/fallbacks
  - [ ] Add tile transformation animations
  - [ ] Implement in-tile password form
  - [ ] Add client-side auth logic and feedback
  - [ ] Add "Remember Me" checkbox to in-tile password form
  - [ ] Implement avatar fallback logic:
    - Use 1st letter of username, or 1st letter of first 2 words if space exists
    - Generate background color based on hash of username
  - [ ] Implement clicking outside active tile to revert it to initial state
  - Success criteria: Functional, animated tile-based login UI
  - Dependencies: Story 1.3, Story 1.3.5

- [ ] **Story 1.5: Implement "First Run" Experience on Login Page**
  - [ ] Add first run state determination
  - [ ] Create UI for first run options
  - [ ] Implement passwordless admin login flow
  - [ ] Create admin password setup page
  - [ ] Add session termination for canceled setup
  - [ ] Ensure User.lastLoginAt is only updated after successful password setup
  - [ ] Add disabled "Restore System from Backup" button with tooltip
  - [ ] Implement comprehensive error handling for the first run flow
  - Success criteria: First run experience allows admin setup with password creation
  - Dependencies: Story 1.4

- [ ] **Story 1.6: Implement Basic Protected Routes, Middleware, and Client-Side Session Validation**
  - [ ] Create Next.js middleware
  - [ ] Configure route protection
  - [ ] Implement session/account status checking
  - [ ] Add client-side proactive session validation
  - [ ] Configure matcher for protected routes:
    - '/dashboard/:path*'
    - '/settings/:path*'
    - '/admin/:path*'
  - [ ] Ensure middleware checks both authentication and User.isActive status
  - [ ] Implement client-side session validation in root layout to check session.user.isActive
  - [ ] Add logic to automatically sign out and redirect if user becomes inactive
  - Success criteria: Protected routes secure, inactive users can't access protected content
  - Dependencies: Story 1.3

## Affected Components

- Project structure and configuration files
- Authentication system (NextAuth.js)
- Database schema (Prisma)
- Login UI components
- Middleware for route protection
- Client-side session validation
- UserSetting model and integration
- Environment variable configuration

## Dependencies

- Next.js 15.2.2
- TypeScript 5
- ESLint v9
- Prettier
- Husky and commitlint
- Prisma ORM v6.5.0
- NextAuth.js v4
- SQLite
- bcryptjs for password hashing
- Zod for API validation

## Technical Considerations

- Session management must use HTTP-only cookies
- Password hashing requires secure implementation
- "First Run" experience must maintain secure state transitions
- Must ensure middleware correctly validates both authentication and isActive status
- UserSetting record must be created in the same transaction as User creation
- Consider implementing database transactions for multi-step database operations
- Plan for comprehensive testing of authentication flows and middleware
- Remember to document all environment variables and their purposes

